Class Home

  • java.lang.Object
    • Home

  • public class Home
extends java.lang.Object
    This class represents a Home. It contains many cuboidal rooms, which are made of 6 Walls.
    Version:
    7th February, 2019
    Author:
    Omkar Kanade, Srihari Raju, Varun Yeligar

    • Field Detail

      • rooms

        public Room[] rooms
        This is an array of Rooms. It is initialized with maxNoOfRooms in the constructor.

      • roomCount

        private int roomCount
        This is used to maintain the count of the rooms in a House. The count is initialized with roomCount in the constructor.

      • houseNumber

        private int houseNumber
        This represents the house number which is unique for each Home.

      • baseLength

        private int baseLength
        This represents the length of the entire Home inside which the rooms are constructed.

      • baseWidth

        private int baseWidth
        This represents the width of the entire Home inside which the rooms are constructed.

      • height

        protected static int height
        This represents the height of the Home. This height is same for all the rooms of the Home. This variable should have protected access and must be static type.

    • Constructor Detail

      • Home

        public Home(int maxNoOfRooms,
            int houseNumber,
            int baseLength,
            int baseWidth,
            int height,
            int roomCount)
        Constructor for objects of class Home. All variables are initialised with the values given.
        Parameters:
        maxNoOfRooms - The array rooms[] is initialised with maxNoOfRooms.
        houseNumber - specifies the houseNumber of the Home.
        baseLength - Denotes the length of the base of the entire home
        baseWidth - Denotes the width of the base of the entire home
        height - Denotes the height of the home. Note that height of all homes is same
        roomCount - Denotes the count of rooms in the Home

    • Method Detail

      • getHouseNumber

        the houseNumber of the house

      • getCountRooms

        public int getCountRooms()

      • getBadWalls

        public int getBadWalls()
        This method aims to return the total number of bad walls in each room of the house. For example, if there are 2 rooms and both rooms have 4 bad walls, then return 8.
        Returns:
        Returns the total number of bad walls in each room of the house.

      • getBadWalls

        public int getBadWalls(int roomNo)
        This method aims to return the total number of bad walls in the room with the given index (roomNo) If the roomNo exceeds the roomCount, then return -1
        Returns:
        Returns the total number of bad walls in the given room of the home if roomNo is valid, else -1.

      • houseVolume

        public int houseVolume()
        The volume of the home is given by baseLength*baseWidth*height
        Returns:
        Returns the volume of the home.

      • freeSpace

        public int freeSpace()
        The free space in the home is the unconstructed part of the home. It is possible that the home is not completely constructed, that is, the sum of volumes of all the rooms may not equal the volume of the home. So we want you to find the empty/free space in the home.
        Returns:
        Returns the free space in the home.
